<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Lotus scoparius </i>is a short-lived shrub that can reach 20 years of age. This legume is a nitrogen fixer. The thin, sparsely leaved stems form open rounded plants that bloom from spring through summer with yellow flowers. Fruits are indehiscent and dispersed passively short distances. Forming a seed bank, seeds germinate with disturbance (Montalvo 2003).<br/>
<br/>
<i>Lupinus albifrons </i>is a large shrubby lupine with silvery leaves. The flowers are loosely whorled, and the bi-colored purple and white flowers are large and showy. The eight varieties vary in habit and leaf characters and are somewhat isolated geographically. Var. <i>abramsii </i>(a CNPS 3.2 plant) and vars. <i>austromontanus, douglasii, hallii, johnstonii</i>and <i>medius </i>are restricted; var. <i>albifrons </i>and var. <i>collinus </i>are common. Sampling over the entire range of the species is needed to understand their role in the state’s vegetation. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriodictyon californicum </i>is a much-branched, evergreen shrub that attains 2.5 m. Branches are resinous, and leaves are glutinous and lanceolate. A sooty fungus often blackens mature leaves of <i>E. californicum</i>. Seeds collect near plants, forming a seed bank, and they germinate following a disturbance. Seedlings are sensitive to the presence of emerging herbs, which competitively replace most emerging <i>E. californicum </i>seedlings. Plants regenerate asexually through rhizomes, and roots are shallow (Howard 1992e). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriodictyon crassifolium </i>is a much-branched, evergreen shrub that attains 3 m in height. Branches are tomentose, and the lanceolate leaves are entire to toothed, sparsely hairy to white-tomentose. Plants probably have a similar ecology to that of <i>E. californicum, </i>whereby seeds collect near plants and form a seed bank; they germinate following disturbance such as fire, and plants die after 20 to 30 years (Howard 1992e). Then other chaparral shrubs such as <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum </i>become dominant.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Dendromecon rigida </i>is a short-lived shrub that grows to 3 m in height. Seeds are scattered from the plant by violently dehiscing capsules and then transported further by ants (Berg 1966). Ants cache and discard the seeds on open sites providing uphill, downhill, and interdrainage dispersal (Bullock 1989). Seedlings establish after fire or other disturbances. Plants are ephemeral and replaced by longer-lived chaparral species in time.<br/>
<br/>
The diagnostic species of this alliance are early colonizers of disturbed sites throughout cismontane-California. Stands represent a natural phase of post-fire regeneration in California chaparral, as do those of the <i>Malacothamnus fasciculatus - Malacothamnus </i>spp. Alliance.  For example, <i>Lotus scoparius </i>dominates recently burned patches of chaparral and coastal scrub (e.g., <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum, Artemisia californica - (Salvia leucophylla), </i>and <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum </i>alliances).<br/>
 <br/>
<i>Lupinus albifrons </i>is relatively short-lived and tends to colonize regularly disturbed, steep and unstable slopes and shifting sands. Stands are typically open and regularly occur on rocky surfaces with little soil development, including road cuts and active alluvium as well as relatively long-persisting stands on rock outcrops. They occur in the central Sierra Nevada foothills on exposed, steep slopes including limestone. Stands also occur in the central Coast Ranges on rocky, alluvial surfaces, and on the Channel Islands on unstable sandy substrates.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Eriodictyon californicum </i> regularly forms stands in recently burned chaparral, in grazed or cleared shrublands, or other disturbed areas. In the Sierra Nevada foothills, these seral stands become invaded by other shrubs or trees as they age, and stands transition to shrublands, such as <i>Ceanothus cuneatus </i> or <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum </i>Alliances, or woodlands, such as <i>Quercus douglasii </i>or <i>Q. wislizeni </i>Aliances, with lack of disturbance (Klein et al. 2007). <i>E. crassifolium</i> also germinates after fire and represents this alliance in warmer regions of southern California where it is otherwise uncommon. Other related species, such as <i>Eriodictyon parryi</i>occur in similar habitats as well.<br/>
<br/>
In the 2009 book, <i>A Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i>, <i>Lotus scoparius, Lupinus albifrons, Eriodictyon californicum, E. crassifolium, </i>and <i>Dendromecon rigida </i>were treated separately in their own respective alliances. More recent analyses have expanded our understanding of these disturbance-related vegetation types and demonstrated their close similarity to one another. This merger of alliances also reflects a broader alliance treatment, which is a general trend for the revised USNVC (NatureServe 2020). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
