<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">The alliance is a disturbance-stimulated type. <i>Eriodictyon californicum </i>establishes after low to moderate severity fires by sprouting from rhizomes. <i>Lotus scoparius </i>or <i>Lupinus albifrons</i> does not sprout after fire (Keeley and Keeley 1984). Generally, they are obligate seeders. <i>Eriodictyon californicum </i>also readily germinates after fire from seeds that lie dormant in the soil for decades. Fire scarifies seeds with heat stimulating germination, burns off the litter layer, and exposes seeds to sufficient light to allow germination. Seedlings rapidly grow within the first few years after fire. Plants can flower with seedlings establishing within the second year (Montalvo and Ellstrand 2001). <i>L. scoparius </i>seedlings are notably larger than other shrub seedlings in the second season after fire (Keeley and Keeley 1984), and dense stands can occur within 2-3 years after fire. This early seral, short-lived shrub relinquishes dominance to longer-lived shrubs usually 5-10 years after fire (Montalvo 2003) and some stands persist in areas with repeated fires (Howard 1992e).

We know little about optimum conditions for <i>Dendromecon rigida </i>stands. Stands are usually small (< 2 ha) and occur in openings in chaparral. Stands may be associated with largely sprouting or obligate-seeding chaparral shrubs. <i>Dicentra chrysantha, Helianthus gracilentus, </i>or other fire followers are often present.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
