		<tr>
			<td class="key">Severity</td>
			<td>Low to very high
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Type</td>
			<td>Passive-independent crown fire
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Regional knowledge</td>
			<td>Cismontane California; Sonoran Desert; Baja California
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
	</table>
</div>



    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa, Ac-l). Stands generally intermix with coastal scrub and grasslands throughout the section an become established after fire and along fire lines and road cuts, including those at the Big Creek Reserve in Monterey Co. (UC Natural Reserve System 2003), which are dense.  Recorded stands in San Mateo County (Sikes et al. 2021) and expected stands along the central coast (CCH 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-f, Ah-k). Mapped and recorded stands in Pinnacles National Park (Kittel et al. 2012), Carrizo National Monument (Buck-Diaz and Evens 2011a), and the Clear Creek Management Area (Evens et al. 2006).</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Cb). Stands of <i>Lotus scoparius</i> occur at Anza- Borrego Desert State Park where it occurs adjacent to both desert scrub and chaparral stands in the western portions of the park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ae, Ag-h, Ak-l, Ao, Aq, As, Au, Az). Recorded stands exist in sandy areas in the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta area, including the Antioch Dunes.  Recorded and mapped stands around the edges of the Great Valley of Eriodictyon californicum in the Sacramento Valley and Lupinus albifrons in the San Joaquin Valley, including stands along the San Joaquin River (Buck-Diaz et al. 2012). Expected stands on the slopes of Sutter Buttes (CCH 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ai). Expected stands occur near Lake Shasta occur in recently burned areas on south-facing slopes and have also been observed at Whiskeytown Reservoir.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ag, An). Mapped stands of Eriodictyon crassifolium and Dendromecon rigida just at the southern edge of these subsections, on the northern feet of the San Gabriel and San Bernadino Mountain ranges (Menke et al. 2013).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ac, Af-g, Aj, Al-m). Stands occur on roadbanks and steep eroded slopes through the central and southern subsections. In the southern subsections, stands also occur in chaparral.  Mapped and recorded stands in both Marin and Sonoma Counties (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021; Klein et al. 2015).  Expected stands farther north based on CCH records (CCH 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-f). Stands occur in and adjacent to chaparral throughout the section.
Stands have been observed in the Yolla Bolly Mountains (Be) below 1500 m and in eastern Napa Co. (Bf) on steep southwest-facing slopes surrounded by <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> and <i>Ceanothus cuneatus</i> alliance.  Recorded and mapped stands in both Sonoma and Napa Counties (Klein et al. 2015; Thorne et al. 2004; VegCAMP 2014c).  Expected stands in northern areas of subsections based on CCH records (CCH 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). Mapped stands in Napa County, including the Knoxville Wildlife Area (Thorne et al. 2004; VegCAMP 2014c).  Expected stands in northern areas of subsections based on CCH records (CCH 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ef-g, Ep, Er-s). Recorded and mapped stands of Lupinus albifrons near Yosemite National Park and in Tehachapi (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b; VegCAMP 2015a).  Expected stands in other subsections based on CCH records (CCH 2017).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Mapped and recorded stands throughout region (Klein et al. 2007; Ratchford et al. 2021a; VegCAMP 2015a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands exist after disturbance in the section, including in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006), along the Santa Clara River and Sespe Creek (Stillwater Sciences and URS 2007), and coastal terraces south to the Mexican border (Evens and San 2005). Stands also occur on coastal dunes and steep banks. Stands of <i>Lupinus albifrons </i> in the northern Channel Islands (Johnson and Rodriguez 2001, Junak et al. 2007) occupy stabilized dunes and coastal bluffs.  Stands in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) are similar to those across the section, occurring on moderately steep slopes largely associated with sprouting shrubs of <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum, Heteromeles arbutifolia, Rhus ovata,</i> and <i>Quercus berberidifolia.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-d, Bf-g, Bi-p). Mapped and recorded stands throughout region (Klein and Evens 2005; Sproul et al. 2011; Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Although stands are often a natural phase post-disturbance in California, <i>Eriodictyon californicum </i>can become dominant on heavily used rangelands, particularly in areas of chaparral converted to grassland (Howard 1992e). Similarly, <i>Lotus scoparius </i> and <i>Lupinus albifrons </i>are able to establish quickly in disturbed areas from seed. Thus, they can be useful for post-fire recovery, erosion control, and habitat restoration in California. In choosing seed source for restoration, seeds have a higher fitness and success at establishing when they come from local or nearby sources populations (Montalvo and Ellstrand 2001). Further, <i>L. scoparius </i>provides important forage for deer, especially in drought years (Dale 2000). 

A fungal pathogen impacts the long-term health of <i>Lupinus albifrons </i>in some parts of its range. This fungus has raised concern due to the reliance of the endangered mission blue butterfly (<i>Icaricia icarioides missionensis</i>) on <i>L. albifrons </i>as a larval food plant. Studies currently being undertaken at Point Reyes National Seashore will determine the significance of the disease on the plant and butterfly (see Point Reyes National Seashore website). 

The characteristic species of this alliance are seed-banking species, therefore abnormally high fire frequencies would eliminate seed banks of this and later seral chaparral species. </div>
</div>

    

    

